sublevels.theory:
Unlike arrays (which hold many variables of the *same* type), a **struct** allows you to group different data types together under a single name. Structs are the closest thing C has to objects or classes.

```c
struct Player {
    int health;
    float speed;
    char name[50];
};
```
To declare a variable of this custom type in `main`, you must use the `struct` keyword:
`struct Player p1;`

You access the individual fields belonging to `p1` using the **`.` (Dot) Operator**:
```c
p1.health = 100;
p1.speed = 4.5;
strcpy(p1.name, "Hero");
```

**Struct Padding & Packing**: The compiler will automatically insert empty "padding" bytes between struct members so that variables align perfectly with your CPU's memory read lanes (e.g., placing 4-byte ints on addresses neatly divisible by 4). This makes CPU reads faster, but wastes RAM. You can disable this with `__attribute__((packed))` on GCC.

**`typedef struct`**:
To avoid typing the annoyance keyword `struct` every time you declare a variable, C devs commonly create a type definition synonym: 
```c
typedef struct {
    int x;
    int y;
} Point;

Point p1; // No 'struct' keyword needed anymore!
```
